Lesson SEARCH SUMMARY



  1. */# - search word under cursor. g*/g# - search inword under cursor.

  2. :g/ERROR - show all lines in new window
     :g/GET \/noise/d - delete noise lines
     :%s/ERROR//gn - count ERROR

  3. Both VIMGREP and RIPGREP help you build a quickfix list.

    3.1 Quickfix

     Quickfix list = searchable results table:
     file | line | column | matched text

     Quickfix navigation:
     :vimgrep /ERROR/gj %

     :copen
     :cnext
     :cprev
     :cfirst
     :clast
     :cclose
     :cc - show current quickfix item
     :cclose - close quickfix
     :cwindow - open quickfix only if there are results

     Use location list when you want separate search results per split/window:
     :lvimgrep /ERROR/gj %

     :lopen
     :lnext
     :lprev
     :lclose

    3.2 vimgrep

     vimgrep is Vim/Neovim’s built-in grep.
     \v - regex-friendly mode
     \V - literal text mode.

     Examples:

     :vimgrep /ERROR/ %

     :vimgrep /pattern/gj files - `g` collect all matches on a line, not only first. `j` do not jump immediately to first match.

     :vimgrep /\v(ERROR|WARN|Exception|Traceback)/gj % - Search several patterns

     :vimgrep /ERROR/gj *.log - Search multiple files

     :vimgrep /ERROR/gj **/*.log - Search recursively

     :vimgrep /ERROR/gj %
     :vimgrepadd /WARN/gj % - Add to existing results

     vimgrep is good, but:
     - It can be slower on huge folders.
     - It uses Vim regex, not modern regex.
     - It searches through files using Vim itself.
     - For massive logs, external tools are better.
     For one open file, vimgrep is great.

    3.3 repgrep

     The ! in :grep! means: fill quickfix but do not jump immediately.

     :grep! "ERROR|WARN" logs/

     :grep! "request_id=abc-123" logs/

     :grep! "ERROR|WARN|Exception|Traceback" logs/

     :grep! "status(_code)?[=: ]+5[0-9][0-9]" logs/ - Search HTTP 5xx

     :grep! -F "user.id" logs/ - literal text mode

     :grep! -e "connection refused" -e "connection reset" -e "timed out" logs/ - multiple patterns

     :grep! "ERROR" -g "*.log" logs/ - searche with globs

     :grep! "ERROR" -g "*.log" -g "*.txt" logs/

     :grep! "ERROR" -g "*.log" -g "!*.gz" logs/ - exclude gz files

     :grep! "ERROR" -g "!*compose*" logs/ - exciude health files

     :grep! -u "ERROR" logs/ - search ignorring hidden files
     -u - search ignored files
     -uu - search ignored + hidden files
     -uuu - search ignored + hidden + binary files

